<TEXT>
teachers carried picket signs in more than 20 public school 
districts in four states tuesday many held out for raises and the 
biggest pay demand 42 percent over three years drew the ire of a 
mayor as irresponsible 
the teachers decided its time to take a stand and that stand 
actually is a walk and thats what well be doing tomorrow morning 
walking a picket line said thomas grady head of the united 
teachers of lowell mass after a unanimous strike vote there 
tuesday the first day of school was canceled wednesday for the 
citys 13100 pupils 
nationally walkouts affected more than 100000 pupils in 
michigan pennsylvania massachusetts and illinois a strike in its 
third week in louisiana was settled tuesday night 
more than 1400 professors and academic staff members at wayne 
state university in detroit also went on strike tuesday over union 
work rules and salary university president david adamany predicted 
classes for the roughly 30000 students would continue with other 
fulltime and parttime instructors but professors said they 
expected few classes to be held 
an additional 950 clerical workers and secretaries represented 
by the united auto workers have been on strike at wayne state since 
aug 25 
in pontiac mich bargainers representing 991 teachers met with 
school officials through the weekend with no success major issues 
were class size and salary with teachers asking for a 10 percent 
raise and being offered 2 percent michigan education association 
spokeswoman colleen hudgens said 
superintendent labarbara gragg said monday night that talks 
would be scheduled later in the week meanwhile classes that 
opened sept 1 were canceled tuesday for pontiacs 17284 students 
as teachers picketed deputy superintendent byron love said 
in state college pa 415 teachers staged the first strike in 
the districts history said union spokesman george apaliski about 
5900 students missed the scheduled opening day of school tuesday 
we are not at all close district spokeswoman patricia best 
said its very discouraging the school board offered a 33 
percent raise over three years ms best said the state college 
area education association has not made public its pay demand 
in massachusetts teachers in nearly 40 school districts are 
going to work this week without a contract the only strike votes 
taken however were in lowell and peabody teacher strikes are 
illegal in massachusetts 
officials canceled the first day of school for 13100 pupils 
wednesday in lowell mass after the districts 970 teachers voted 
unanimously to strike for more pay and to preserve longevity 
bonuses 
in peabody the citys 408 teachers rejected a 17 percent wage 
increase over three years and held out for 42 percent over the same 
time span 
to sit at the table locked in at 42 percent is totally 
irresponsible said peabody mayor peter torigian 
school superintendent james buckley said administrators were 
trying to bring in enough substitutes to keep classes going 
bert latessa of the massachusetts federation of teachers 
defended the unions position the 42 percent wage request latessa 
said is smaller than it appears because the teachers maintain that 
they have been performing extra duties such as elementary 
preparation and handling oversized classes without extra pay 
here was the picture by statebystate 
michigan strikes in 10 districts idled nearly 45000 students 
and more than 2000 teachers the michigan education association 
said 
pennsylvania strikes by about 2200 teachers in nine districts 
affected about 36000 students according to george badner of the 
pennsylvania education association 
