<TEXT>
after a week of refining his message and 
selling it to friendly audiences republican vice presidential 
nominee dan quayle is home preparing for the fall campaign 
following a patriotic season opener at the statue of liberty 
quayle is spending time with his family today and holds staff 
meetings wednesday before taking a quick swing to illinois and ohio 
at weeks end 
the indiana senator delivered a labor day tribute monday to the 
pledge of allegiance which the republicans have attempted to turn 
into a political weapon against democratic presidential nominee 
michael dukakis 
quayle blasted dukakis for vetoing a massachusetts bill that 
would have penalized teachers who did not lead their students in 
the pledge 
the values embodied in the pledge deserve to be transmitted to 
our children quayle said 
to us they are not hokey or cornball or passe he said 
quayle also toured ellis island where millions of immigrants 
entered the country and which is now undergoing restoration the 
quayles are of scottish descent and their relatives did not come 
through ellis island but the couple and their three children posed 
for photographs anyway with a group of people dressed in costumes 
of their native countries 
quayles speech at the base of lady liberty with the manhattan 
skyline in the background and ellis island nearby was planned as a 
moving kickoff to the countdown to election day 
but it was disrupted briefly by about 30 demonstrators members 
of a coalition that believes the reagan administration and quayle 
have not done enough in the fight against aids 
quayles aides said later that the senator had an exemplary 
record on aids issues and had recently voted to provide 12 
billion in funding for aids research education and prevention 
the demonstrators however said quayle voted against 
legislation to give the experimental drug azt to aids victims 
quayles speech outlined what will be his themes this fall the 
economy is doing well inflation and interest rates are under 
control and earnings and job growth are up 
quayles task will be to sell the voters on the idea that they 
will enjoy a bright future if they stick with the republicans 
according to campaign strategists that was the message quayle had 
for the liberty island crowd 
we will win this election because we are the party of the 
future we believe in our families we believe in the future and we 
believe in preserving freedom in this country we will never let it 
go he said 
it was the same message quayle worked on last week during his 
southern campaign swing speaking before largely sympathetic 
audiences on conservative college campuses and elsewhere in the 
deep south 
