<TEXT>
ruled by the worlds youngest monarch 
tiny swaziland marked 20 years of independence today as a nation 
rich in tradition and largely free of the turbulence that plagues 
its neighbors 
wedged between south africa and mozambique this kingdom of 
rolling hills and lush valleys has spent the past two decades 
pursuing both westernstyle modernization and preservation of 
ageold customs 
progress means a new cocacola bottling plant in the capital of 
mbabane video cassette recorders in the expanding shops and luxury 
tourist hotels 
tradition meanwhile calls for regular celebrations with 
singing and dancing by barebreasted maidens in tribute to 
20yearold spearwielding king mswati iii and his mother known as 
the great she elephant 
for these festive occasions including a ninehour independence 
celebration planned today at the countrys main stadium both men 
and women appear in traditional red orange and yellow skirts with 
long strands of beads and feathers in their hair 
the men carry animal skin shields the women wear beehive 
hairnets 
the babyfaced king who already has four wives was barely four 
months old when his nation received independence from britain on 
sept 6 1968 
two years ago he replaced his father the late king sobhuza ii 
who ruled for 62 years and had at least 68 sons 
economically landlocked swaziland remains an agricultural 
nation heavily dependent on south africa which borders it on three 
sides 
thousands of swazi men work in south africas mines and the vast 
majority of swazilands imports reach the country via its powerful 
neighbor 
a handful of foreign firms that disinvested from south africa 
such as cocacola have moved their plants to swaziland another 
approach has been for firms in south africa to falsely label their 
goods as made in swaziland to evade embargoes against south 
africa 
canada has received made in swaziland wine even though 
there are no vineyards in swaziland citrus produce amounting to 
four times swazilands annual output has turned up with swazi 
labels in the middle east 
swazilands eastern neighbor mozambique offers access to the 
indian ocean and alternatives to south africa transport routes but 
mozambiques main contribution at present is an unwelcome one 
more than 100000 refugees who have fled into swaziland from famine 
and civil war in their country 
swaziland half the size of belgium has two refugee centers 
designed to hold just a few thousand people 
aside from the refugees who swell the countrys population by 
about 15 percent swaziland is ethnically homogenous and has 
avoided the intertribal strife that has plagued many other african 
countries 
the relatively few indidents of political violence in recent 
years generally have involved antiapartheid activists and 
guerrillas from south africa who on occasion have been targets of 
crossborder raids and kidnappings by south african agents 
the king and the royal family have the final say on all major 
matters but most daytoday business is left in the hands of the 
cabinet parliament and the bureaucracy which conduct the 
political affairs with a distinctive swazi touch 
when the parliamentary electoral college was selected last 
november members were chosen by voters who passed through cattle 
gates next to the candidate of their choice 
when retired white farmer rex baxter and his wife arrived to 
vote policemen grabbed him placed him at a gate and told him he 
had been chosen as a candidate while being whisked away for 
weeklong private consultations with the other winners baxter 
shouted to his wife to bring his heart tablets and cigarettes from 
home 
