<TEXT>
the fatal crash landing of a chinese jetliner 
has fired up debate on replacing hong kongs airport known for its 
harrowing flight path that skims the rooftops of crowded kowloon 
peninsula 
the britishbuilt trident jetliner skidded off hong kong 
international airports sole runway into the sea in a torrential 
downpour aug 31 killing seven people in hong kongs worst air 
accident in 21 years 
the accident came at a time when the british colony is 
considering construction of a new airport away from congested urban 
areas the government is funding three surveys to evaluate various 
proposals 
the colonys governor sir david wilson said immediately 
following the crash that it should have no bearing on the future of 
the existing airport which is known as kai tak 
the englishlanguage south china morning post newspaper agreed 
but noted in an editorial that there is no doubt that the crash 
will focus renewed attention on the apparently neverending saga of 
hong kongs need for expanded aviation facilities 
kai tak is squeezed between the sea and the impossibly crowded 
neighborhoods of kowloon one of the colonys major urban areas 
the runway juts into hong kongs famed harbor and is surrounded on 
three sides by water 
use of the airport has expanded rapidly last year 127 million 
passengers were handled an increase of 20 percent from the year 
before and nearly 50 percent from 1982 movement of aircraft 
reached 73370 planes in 1986 an increase of 132 percent from the 
previous year 
the single runway required to handle an aircraft every 180 
seconds during peak hours has exhausted its possibilities the 
morning post said the government says the runway can handle up to 
30 planes an hour 
victor sit a university of hong kong professor who studies 
urban problems expressed concern that the airports enviable 
safety record may run into trouble as traffic increases 
weve been lucky he said so far the accidents all 
happened on the harbor side of the airport not on the landward 
side although the chinese jetliner crashed while approaching the 
runway from the harbor flights typically make their final approach 
over kowloon 
the approach of the airport obviously requires very careful 
maneuvering by the pilots concerned and very precise control by 
the airport sit said passengers rarely forget the final moments 
before touchdown when planes come breathtakingly close to kowloons 
buildings 
kai tak critics note the airport becomes paralyzed whenever the 
runway is disrupted cutting the colonys main transportation link 
to the outside world the chinese jetliner crash stopped traffic 
for about six hours 
they also argue that the airports urban location makes life 
miserable for many local residents a recent study estimated 1 
million people suffer unacceptable noise from kai tak 
government officials have been considering replacement 
possibilities for years and are actively looking at two sites near 
outlying lantau island for a new airport a final decision has been 
promised by the end of 1989 
the most ambitious proposal is from a group led by hopewell 
holdings ltd the massive 308 billionplan would include an 
airport seaport road and railway complex on reclaimed land off 
the islands east coast near hong kong island 
the tiny portuguese territory of macao 40 miles southwest of 
hong kong also has proposed building its own international airport 
and china which regains sovereignty over hong kong in 1997 
plans to construct an airport in its shenzhen special economic zone 
just over the hong kong border sit said that airport would only 
help to ease our trouble a little bit 
he believes kai tak will reach capacity in three to five years 
around the time construction could be starting on a new airport 
unless the government bows to pressure to act faster 
that would mean they only start construction when the airport 
itself has exceeded capacity sit said it would be fairly 
difficult for hong kong to operate as an international financial 
trading and tourist center unless we have some other arrangement 
</TEXT>
