<TEXT>
julie harris who has spent much of the last 
seven years in television has come home to the theater and a 
yearlong tour in driving miss daisy 
not that she had deserted the stage completely while toiling on 
the cbs nighttime soap opera knots landing between seasons as 
the vulnerable often silly and very southern lilimae clements on 
television miss harris found time for short theater engagements 
particularly in her onewoman shows based on the lives of emily 
dickinson and charlotte bronte 
but knots landing occupied most of her career until she was 
written out of the show last fall when last seen on the program 
she and red buttons were riding off into the sunset in a motor home 
now the actress is on the road for real this time in a tour 
that began in detroit after labor day and will end next summer in 
los angeles why submit to the rigors of touring 
its a perfect play miss harris says in describing 
driving miss daisy which chronicles the 25year relationship 
between an elderly atlanta widow and her black chauffeur 
theres an absolute truth about it she adds its 
wellconceived and wellconstructed its like when you look in one 
of those small boxes and there are colors changing all the time 
thats the way working on something like this is its 
neverending the little feelings that eddy out from all the scenes 
go into the next scene 
the play still running offbroadway at the john houseman 
theater was a first effort by alfred uhry and won the 1988 
pulitzer prize for drama touring with miss harris are brock peters 
as the chauffeur and stephen root as her exasperated son 
uhry modeled the woman after his grandmother an elementary 
school teacher he and miss harris talked at length about the woman 
who died in 1973 at the age of 95 he relayed bits and pieces of 
the womans life to give the actress a better understanding of her 
character 
for instance he told me that his grandmothers curiosity was 
such that when she was reading she always had the dictionary beside 
her miss harris recalls she would look up words she didnt 
know be carried away by what she was reading in the dictionary and 
would end up reading that 
miss daisy is only the latest in a long parade of characters 
that the actress has brought to life on stage she has won five 
tony awards for her efforts 
she found small jobs in the theater when she first moved to new 
york in the mid1940s 
i was sort of a young character actress so there was a niche 
for me the oddball girl she recalls 
miss harris astonished broadway in 1950 when she played the 
lonely 12yearold tomboy frankie addams in carson mccullers the 
member of the wedding she was 24 at the time her costar was 
ethel waters in what many consider her greatest role 
ethel waters was a phenomenon of nature miss harris 
recalls she was like the force of niagara falls ive never 
experienced that same power from any other actress 
the next year she won her first tony award as the amoral 
hedonist sally bowles in i am a camera adapted from 
christopher isherwoods berlin stories other tonys arrived for 
her portrayals of joan of ark in the lark a 40yearold 
divorcee falling for a younger man in forty carats mary todd 
lincoln in the last of mrs lincoln and poet emily dickinson in 
the belle of amherst 
miss harris carries on in the old tradition of such acting 
greats as katharine cornell and alfred lunt and lynn fontanne 
performers who go out on the road with their shows 
i guess nothing could intimidate me anymore because i did the 
belle of amherst for so long in huge barns in tiny theaters in 
middlesize theaters and on basketball floors she adds 
i even did six weeks of onenight stands miss harris says 
there was no time to adjust you just slap the makeup on and do 
it some antenna tells you too much voice or too little 
voice 
that instinct for acting was born early 
i once heard an interview with laurence olivier who said both 
his parents loved the theater and so he inherited the wish she 
says that was his expression i think i did too because both 
my parents adored the theater and took us to the theater and talked 
about the theater 
by the time she was 14 she knew she wanted to be an actress 
my parents were very tolerant she says i dont think 
they took it seriously although i did 
miss harris still does even after more than four decades of 
acting 
i try to be adventurous especially in rehearsal she says 
i must try it and something will happen from trying it even if 
what im doing doesnt succeed ive learned the value in saying 
yes to everything eventually you may have to say no but say 
yes first 
that sense of adventure extends to looking for new works too 
today she spends a lot of time reading scripts 
now ive taken an idea for a play to the long wharf theater 
in new haven conn and theyve commissioned it to be written for 
jason robards and me miss harris says the plays about james 
joyce and his wife donald freed will write it but i wont be able 
to do it until late next summer at the very earliest but then 
part of the excitement of life is to work on something new 
</TEXT>
