japan liberalized its financial markets tuesday by 
announcing it would sell 40 percent of its 10year government bonds 
by auction and give foreign underwriters a bigger share of the 
distribution of the rest of the remaining 60 percent 
the steps were favorably received by us officials including 
david c mulford the treasurys assistant secretary for 
international affairs and e gerald corrigan president of the 
federal reserve bank of new york 
the auctions will begin in april 1989 and are expected to make 
it easier for foreign securities firms including americans to get 
a bigger share of the business of selling japanese government debt 
beginning this oct 1 the finance ministry will increase to 
just under 8 percent from 25 percent the share held by 
foreigner underwriters in the syndicate that distributes bonds that 
are not sold by auction 
