<TEXT>
car and truck sales fell 107 percent in august 
compared with the same month last year when incentives called for 
quicker buying decisions by consumers the automakers and analysts 
said tuesday 
foreign and domestic vehicle makers except japans toyota motor 
sales usa inc and south koreas hyundai motor co said they sold 
125 million cars and trucks last month compared with 135 million 
during the same month last year 
for the 10day period ending aug 31 chrysler corp said its 
sales of usmade cars inched up 26 percent compared with the 
same period last year ford motor co meantime said its car sales 
for the period fell 14 percent and general motors corp reported a 
139 percent drop 
each of the big three reported increases in car sales so far 
this calendar year 
toyota spokesman edd snyder said a dealer incentive program that 
stretched through the labor day weekend delayed computation of the 
companys monthly figures hyundais ted kade said tuesday that 
figures for the month hadnt been calculated 
both automakers said their sales figures would be announced 
wednesday 
the kinds of incentives that are on this year are normal 
runofthemill incentives that have been on the cars for a long 
time said auto analyst donald descenza of nomura securities inc 
of new york city 
theres no incentive to buy now to take advantage of current 
incentives he said 
a year ago car makers offered attractive incentives including 
cutrate financing as low as 19 percent for gm vehicles to lure 
customers into showrooms and shrink inventories with just one month 
left in the model year 
those incentives frequently involved shortterm offers such as 
low financing and cashback deals this year the incentives are 
different 
the incentives are sustainable kinds of things descenza 
said incentives have a big impact when its clear to the car 
buyer that they are not going to be around very long 
everybody knew last year they were temporary he added 
that they wouldnt last forever everybody knew that the models 
that qualified for them were in limited supply and dwindling 
rapidly 
tom ogrady president of integrated automotive resources inc 
of wayne pa agreed saying last years incentives colored the 
sales figures this year 
certainly were going to be down in sales from last year 
he said these are certainly very strong sales 
