<TEXT>
a multimilliondollar merger battle over the 
whiskey giant irish distillers group plc was in the balance 
tuesday night after a watchdog body for londons city financial 
district rejected an appeal by european bidders 
the british panel on takeovers and mergers threw out an appeal 
by frances pernod ricard sa against a panel decision allowing 
british rival hotel and leisure group grand metropolitan plc to 
sweeten its hostile bid by launching a knockout bid offer 
the fight is threecornered as british brewers watney mann and 
truman holdings are also seeking to control the irish company 
on wednesday the legal battle shifts to dublin where pernod is 
trying to stop a key shareholder selling its stake to grand met 
after days of suspense pernod formally made a 244 million 
pounds sterling 415 million bid for irish distillers on monday 
but grand met raised its original 180 million pounds 306 million 
offer to 284 million pounds 483 million 
the grand met offer amounts to 525 irish pence a share from an 
earlier 400 irish pence a share the pernod bid is worth only 450 
irish pence a share 
on sunday the executive of the takeover panel ruled that was 
acceptable for grand met because it gave shareholders the 
opportunity to decide the best offer this was despite an earlier 
pledge from grand met not to change its offer in the absence of a 
rival bid 
the full panel on tuesday ended a day of deliberation by backing 
the executives decision and rejecting the pernod appeal 
meanwhile pernod had said it would not be prepared to act as a 
white knight to save irish distillers from grand met unless it 
was pledged the support of 50 percent of irish distillers shares 
at the weekend it believed it had this support holding pledges 
that included one from fruit and vegetable group fii fyffes plc a 
dublin fruit and vegetable merchant which holds 20 percent of 
irish distillers 
but fears that fyffes was about to change its mind and go for 
the higher english offer led pernod to seek a temporary injunction 
from the dublin high court preventing fyffes from selling to grand 
met 
a full hearing of the case will take place wednesday pernod 
says it admits the fyffes promise was not in writing but believes 
it to be legally enforceable 
irish distillers products include irish whiskey brands jamesons 
powers paddy and tullamore 
