<TEXT>
the 3rd us circuit court of appeals on 
tuesday rejected the appeal by a former vice president of litton 
industries inc who was convicted of racketeering in a 63 million 
defense scheme 
roland e fisher 58 of drexel hill faces a sentence of three 
years in prison and a 10000 fine for his participation in one of 
the largest defense fraud cases ever prosecuted by the government 
he was convicted last december of mail fraud racketeering 
obstruction of federal agency proceedings and making false 
statements to a federal agency 
fisher argued in appeal that the evidence against him was 
insufficient and some testimony was prejudicial he also argued 
that he had participated unknowingly in the frauds 
however the appeals court ruled that prosecutors provided ample 
evidence to convict him 
fishers attorney daniel f ryan iii did not return a call for 
comment 
fisher is free on 50000 bail assistant district attorney 
nicholas c harbist said he plans to file a motion soon asking the 
us district court to order fisher to report to prison 
in 1986 litton pleaded guilty to more than 300 counts of 
submitting false claims to the government and 20 counts of mail 
fraud litton agreed to pay 15 million in fines and resitution 
two other officials former purchasing manager joseph diliberto 
and michael millspaugh a former litton controller have pleaded 
guilty in the case 
the men and the company were accused of overcharging the 
government 63 million by inflating costs on contracts for 
military electronics 
